    abstract = {{Early JWST studies reporting an unexpected abundance of massive galaxies at z {\ensuremath{\sim}} 5{\textendash}8 challenge galaxy formation models in the {\ensuremath{\Lambda}}CDM framework. Previous stellar mass (M$\_{{\ensuremath{\star}}}$) estimates suffered from large uncertainties due to the lack of rest-frame near-infrared data. Using deep JWST/NIRCam and Mid-Infrared Instrument (MIRI) photometry from Public Release IMaging for Extragalactic Research, we systematically analyze massive galaxies at z {\ensuremath{\sim}} 3{\textendash}8, leveraging rest-frame {\ensuremath{\gtrsim}}1 {\ensuremath{\mu}}m constraints. We find MIRI is critical for robust M$\_{{\ensuremath{\star}}}$ measurements for massive galaxies at z > 5: excluding MIRI overestimates M$\_{{\ensuremath{\star}}}$ by {\ensuremath{\sim}}0.4 dex on average for M$\_{{\ensuremath{\star}}}$ > {}10$^{10}$M$\_{{\ensuremath{\odot}}}$ galaxies, with no significant effects at lower masses. This reduces number densities of M$\_{{\ensuremath{\star}}}$ > {}10$^{10}$M$\_{{\ensuremath{\odot}}}$ (10$^{10.3}$M$\_{{\ensuremath{\odot}}}$) galaxies by {\ensuremath{\sim}}36\% (55\%). MIRI inclusion also reduces ``Little Red Dot'' (LRD) contamination in massive galaxy samples, lowering the LRD fraction from {\ensuremath{\sim}}32\% to {\ensuremath{\sim}}13\% at M$\_{{\ensuremath{\star}}}$ > 10$^{10.3}$M$\_{{\ensuremath{\odot}}}$. Assuming pure stellar origins, LRDs exhibit M$\_{{\ensuremath{\star}}}$ {\ensuremath{\sim}} 10$^{9{\textendash}10.5}$M$\_{{\ensuremath{\odot}} }$with MIRI constraints, rarely exceeding 10$^{10.5}$M$\_{{\ensuremath{\odot}}}$. Within standard {\ensuremath{\Lambda}}CDM, our results indicate a moderate increase in the baryon-to-star conversion efficiency (ϵ) toward higher redshifts and masses at z > 3. For the most massive z {\ensuremath{\sim}} 8 galaxies, ϵ {\ensuremath{\sim}} 0.3, compared to ϵ {\ensuremath{\lesssim}} 0.2 for typical galaxies at z < 3. This result is consistent with models where high gas densities and short free-fall times suppress stellar feedback in massive high-z halos.}},
